The short answer is:  &quot;Don&#39;t write tests that are interdependant&quot;. 
There&#39;s some nice rants about why you don&#39;t want to do that, but the
short reason is that you don&#39;t know which one is failing.

Your example was an insert/delete method.  Make these separate tests,
possibly in separate TestCase classes.  Change your tests to look for
*separate* data so that failures in the deletion test do not conflict
with the insert test.  As an aside, save yourself some trouble and use
data in your Unit Tests that is also different from your Dev or
Testing data.  The last thing you want is for records you inserted
during your development to conflict with your automated unit tests.

If you find yourself in a situation where you *can&#39;t* refactor them to
be non-interdependant, then reconsider what you&#39;re testing, and see if
the two dependant tests are really one test.  In many insert/delete
situations, I don&#39;t really care that the database changed but that the
expectations of my API hold.  I&#39;ll leave it to the database developers
over at MySQL to make sure it does its job successfully.

Does that help?

-Kevin  


